  "why": "The TACTIC method is explicitly designed to generate plausible and realistic test inputs. It enforces naturalness by using a generative model (MUNIT) trained on real-world images, which learns a 'style space' representing specific environmental conditions. This restricts the search for transformations to a learned plausible distribution. Semantic consistency is enforced by MUNIT's design, which separates an image's domain-invariant 'content' (e.g., road layout) from its domain-specific 'style' (e.g., rain, snow). New test cases are generated by applying a new style to the content of an original seed image. The search process avoids cumulative distortion because each candidate style vector is evaluated by applying it to the original, unmodified set of seed images, rather than to previously mutated images. The paper provides a user study to validate the realism of the generated scenes, further emphasizing that plausibility is a core design goal.",
  "evidence": "Page 2, Section 1: \"To specify the environmental conditions of an environmental type, instead of using configurations, TACTIC employs the Multimodal Unsupervised Image-to-Image Translation (MUNIT) (Huang et al., 2018) to deep-learn the features of environmental conditions from a set of sample scenes belonging to the same environmental type and encode them as a high-dimensional vector space called style space.\"\n\nPage 4, Section 3.1: \"MUNIT is that the representation of images can be decomposed into a content space that is domain-invariant and a style space that captures domain-specific characteristics... the domain-invariant content space will encode the information shared by scenes of the two different environmental types, such as the road information like the shapes of road and the roadside trees.\"\n\nPage 6, Section 3.2.3: \"The ability to detect more erroneous behaviours of a style vector is measured by the mean steering angle divergences between the original dataset of driving scenes and the newly synthesised driving scenes with that style vector. Formally, let g(x, s) be the function that transforms a driving scene x into another in the target environmental type using style vector s... Let Io be the original dataset of driving scenes, the ability of a style vector s to detect more erroneous behaviours is calculated as: Fa(s) = (1/|Io|) * Σ_{x∈Io} |f(x) − f(g(x, s))|.\" This formula shows that transformations are always applied to the original scenes `x` from the dataset `Io`, thus preventing cumulative distortion.\n\nPage 8, Section 4.3: \"We conduct a user study to evaluate the realism of the testing driving scenes synthesised by TACTIC through comparing them with the test driving scenes synthesised by DeepRoad (Zhang et al., 2018), DeepTest (Tian et al., 2018), and PreScan (Marketakis et al., 2009).\""
